    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Responsible Drinking</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Peter H Cresy (Distilled Spirits Council of United States) on Caroline Knapp's June 21 article; notes distillers finance educational organization to spur responsible decision-making regarding alcohol and fight alcohol abuse; holds most Americans who drink do so responsibly</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Caroline Knapp suggests that our culture should be ''honest'' about alcohol (Op-Ed, June 21). We are honest about alcohol. If you choose to drink, you have a moral responsibility to be sensible. If you can't be responsible, then you have no business drinking.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Caroline Knapp suggests that our culture should be ''honest'' about alcohol (Op-Ed, June 21). We are honest about alcohol. If you choose to drink, you have a moral responsibility to be sensible. If you can't be responsible, then you have no business drinking.</p>
        <p>The ill effects of alcohol abuse are well known, and a great many public, private, industry and government-financed organizations are dedicated to eradicating abuse. In fact, this country's leading distillers financed an educational organization, the Century Council, whose purpose is to promote responsible decision-making regarding alcohol and to fight alcohol abuse.</p>
        <p>The vast majority of American adults who choose to drink alcohol do so responsibly. For those 100 million Americans, drinking can be a pleasurable part of a socially acceptable adult lifestyle.</p>
        <p>PETER H. CRESSY  Washington, June 23, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is president and chief executive of the Distilled Spirits Council of the United States.</p>
      </block>
